story.title: Falco - Episode 8
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?
story.creator: web-uploader
story.prePaywallNotification: OMG—the police found a dead body in Stark’s Quarry? Is it Libby Dixon? 😱 Tap back into Hooked to find out.
story.postPaywallNotification: 🤔 Who’s the father of Libby’s baby—Duke, or Bronco? Tap back into Hooked to find out the answer, and to see if it cracks open the case.

messages.text: Investigation: Day 9
The following is a transcript of the press conference held by the Cedar Creek Sheriff’s Office regarding the disappearance of Libby Dixon, conducted June 28, 8:02 AM.
Thanks for being here today, folks.
The Cedar Creek Sheriff’s Office has called this press conference regarding the disappearance of Elizabeth Kay Dixon to fill you in on some recent developments in the case.
The Sheriff’s Office has searched tirelessly for the missing teen.
Each lead was thoroughly exhausted, and no stone has been left unturned.
Unfortunately, the remains recovered yesterday at Stark’s Quarry have been positively identified as those of Libby Dixon.
The coroner conducted an autopsy and concluded that her death was a homicide.
His report states that Libby died of blunt force trauma to the skull.
I am heartbroken for Libby’s family, who ask that you please respect their privacy during this difficult time.
The Sheriff’s Office welcomes tips from our citizens—
And the Dixons have offered a $20,000 reward for anyone who comes forward with information about Libby’s killer.
Someone out there has got to know something about the tragedy that befell this sweet young girl.
Please do the right thing.
Help provide closure for this grieving family.
Help make the streets of Cedar Creek safer.
And help serve justice for the murder of Libby Dixon.
I’m willing to take a few questions from reporters, but I can’t discuss confidential information.
My utmost concern is the integrity of this investigation.
So…who’s got questions for me?
Do you have any suspects, Sheriff?
We’re looking for information anyone has on the alias “Bronco.”
Is Bronco the prime suspect in Libby’s murder?
We’re not ruling anybody out at this point.
Can you verify whether Libby Dixon was pregnant when she was killed?
I decline to comment.
Did Libby seek an abortion prior to her death?
I decline to comment.
Did you find blood in Libby’s vehicle?
There was no blood in or around her vehicle.
Libby Dixon’s injuries were strictly internal.
Did Libby die from falling into the quarry, or was she killed somewhere else?
There were drag marks in the gravel from the road to the quarry.
We believe that she passed away before her body was disposed of.
Did you recover forensic evidence at the quarry?
I decline to comment.
Is your son Duke Simmons a suspect, Sheriff?
I decline to comment.
Is your son involved in Libby’s death?
I decline to comment.
Does he have an alibi?
Okay, folks. That’s enough.
The Sheriff’s Office won’t be taking any more questions at this time.
Thank you for your cooperation in this serious matter. We’ve set up an anonymous tip line at 555-0943.
Please share whatever information you may have that could help us find Libby’s killer.
I appreciate your time and concern.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 28, 1:22 PM.
You out at Stark’s Quarry, boss?
I’m still not your boss, Decker.
But yes. Look how clear the water is.
Agent Falco sends Deputy Decker a photograph of a quarry. The site has been flooded with deep, clear groundwater.
This site is abandoned, correct?
Yeah. It hasn’t been an active quarry for decades now.
I can’t believe a swimmer found her.
It doesn’t seem safe to swim out here.
It’s certainly not.
Technically, the swimmer was trespassing — that’s probably why he remained anonymous.
Could be.
I talked to the coroner this afternoon.
He confirmed Libby’s pregnancy. She was about six weeks along.
Shit. That poor girl.
So six weeks…
And she disappeared on June 18.
She must’ve conceived sometime around the week of May 5.
Yeah, I think so.
That would’ve been after her depressive episode in March.
So she didn’t overdose because of a pregnancy.
I reckon not.
She was dating Duke at the time of conception.
She didn’t break things off with him ‘til May.
You think it could be his baby?
I don’t know. But we could test the fetal DNA, assuming the coroner was able to recover any.
We’d have to get a sample from Duke to compare it to.
Simmons won’t allow that if we tell him we’re looking at Duke as a suspect.
Okay, so tell him it’s an exclusionary sample—
Get him to think that Bronco is our only suspect.
And we just need to prove Duke’s not Bronco.
Okay. I’ll talk to Simmons and see if I can get him to cooperate.
Tell me how it goes.
Does Libby’s family know that the pregnancy’s been confirmed?
Yeah. Simmons broke the news to them a few minutes ago.
How’d they take it?
About how you’d expect, I guess.
Darrence threw a chair across the interview room.
Lynette sobbed uncontrollably.
Anna Mae looked as white as a sheet.
Probably in shock or something.
You find anything at the quarry?
No. The gravel’s too loose for these footprints to be identifiable.
Take a look.
Agent Falco sends a photograph of vague imprints in loose gravel.
So we’re shit out of luck.
Don’t give up on me yet, Tex Decker.
Did the coroner provide an approximate date of death?
Yeah. He said that bodies decompose much faster in freshwater than on land.
Really?
Some scientists think the maggots thrive in the cool water.
Especially in hot weather like we’ve had.
I saw the autopsy photos.
There was some bone exposure.
Yeah. The desiccated tissue helped the coroner narrow down the time of death.
He said it’s likely she’d be totally skeletonized had she been in the water more than 9 to 12 days.
So she died approximately 9 to 12 days ago.
According to the coroner, yeah.
Okay.
But if Libby’s been dead at least 9 days, then who the hell did the clerk see at Wired?
That, boss, is the million-dollar question.
The following is an email exchange between Sidney Pickett and Agent Falco.
The following is an audio call from Director Philomena Todd to Agent Falco, placed June 28, 7:12 PM.
Falco.
Hi, Frankie. It’s Philomena Todd. I’ve got some news on the Dixon case.
Okay, yeah?
I received the copy of the autopsy report you sent me earlier. I was alarmed to learn of the girl’s pregnancy.
I had some indications of the possibility, but nothing concrete prior to the autopsy.
We lucked out on the fetal DNA. Any more time in the water and the evidence would’ve been gone.
The coroner sent the sample over to the state lab for testing, and I called them myself to put a rush on the results.
It’s already been tested?
It can take weeks, if not months, to get the lab to process DNA.
Let’s just say I called in a favor, okay?
The lab sent the results to me about an hour ago, and there’s a hit in the system — a familial match.
The child is related to an offender in CODIS?
Yes. The offender’s DNA was collected three years ago. He was arrested for a DUI in Clarksville.
Tennessee only collects DNA in felony DUIs — was there a death involved?
No, but he had a minor friend in the car with him who suffered some extensive injuries.
They charged him with “child endangerment with bodily injury.”
A Class D Felony.
Exactly. He was incarcerated in Memphis from 2014 to 2016 and then moved to Cedar Creek to live with his father, a local mechanic.
The boy’s name is Jimmy Fitz.
Oh, my god — wait.
What is it?
Jimmy Fitz was dating Libby’s older sister, Anna Mae.
Looks like he was dating Libby, too, huh?
If Jimmy Fitz is related to Libby’s unborn child, he must be the father.
Indeed.
So this means—
Jimmy Fitz is “Bronco.”
